First, we notice that $(0,\greenD{-6})$ is the $y$-intercept. Second, we use the two points to find the slope:

$\begin{align}
\text{Slope}&=\dfrac{10-(-6)}{4-0}
\\\\\
&=\dfrac{16}{4}
\\\\
&=\maroonC 4
\end{align}$

Now we can write the equation in slope-intercept:

$y=\maroonC{4}x\greenD{-6}$

We can see the line passes through $(0,5)$ and $(3,-4)$.

So $(0,\greenD{5})$ is the $y$-intercept. Now let's use the two points to find the slope:

$\begin{align}
\text{Slope}&=\dfrac{-4-5}{3-0}
\\\\\
&=\dfrac{-9}{3}
\\\\
&=\maroonC{-3}
\end{align}$

Now we can write the equation in slope-intercept:

$y=\maroonC{-3}x\greenD{+5}$
